{
  "texts": [
    "The concept of sequestering carbon within permanent building structures is gaining recognition as a promising avenue for research.",
    "In the context of the biochar cycle, sourcing bio-based materials from sustainable forests is typically viewed as carbon-neutral (Liu et al. 2023b).",
    "This is because the harvested biomass is replaced by new tree growth, and the carbon dioxide absorbed during the growth period is roughly equivalent to the carbon dioxide released at the end of the biomass product's life cycle.",
    "Consequently, assuming time is not factored into the life cycle assessment, the carbon neutrality of bio-based products implies an eventual achievement of climate-carbon neutrality.",
    "The harvested biomass is regenerated in new trees, and the amount of carbon dioxide absorbed during rotation is roughly the same as the amount of carbon dioxide released at the end of the life of the biomass product."
  ]
}